// @test: parse
// @level: L1
// @tier: 0
// @description: Higher inductive types — path constructors — T1-U.
//
// In Book HoTT, a higher inductive type (HIT) declares not only
// point constructors but also *path constructors* — elements of
// `Path<T>(a, b)` that identify otherwise-distinct points. This
// gives a uniform account of quotients, truncations, coequalizers,
// and the canonical spheres S¹, S², … of homotopy theory.
//
// Verum's HIT syntax accepts two equivalent spellings for a path
// constructor — both already used across `core/math/hott.vr`:
//   `| loop: Path<S1>(base, base)`
//   `| loop() = base..base`
//
// Variant names can be drawn from Verum's keyword space so the
// canonical HoTT constructor names (`loop`, `merid`, `trunc_path`,
// `push`) work directly.

// The circle S¹ — one point, one non-trivial loop.
public type S1 is
    | base
    | loop: Path<S1>(base, base);

// Suspension: north, south, and a path for each a: A.
public type Susp<A> is
    | north
    | south
    | merid(a: A): Path<Susp<A>>(north, south);

// Propositional truncation `||A||` — free proposition on A.
public type Trunc<A> is
    | trunc_in(a: A)
    | trunc_path: fn(x: Trunc<A>, y: Trunc<A>) -> Path<Trunc<A>>(x, y);

// 2-sphere S² — encoded as a HIT with a 2-dimensional surface
// constructor.
public type S2 is
    | base2
    | surf: Path<Path<S2>(base2, base2)>(refl(base2), refl(base2));

fn main() { }
